{
  "card_id": "price_action",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Price Action",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "Analysis of raw price movement on a chart without relying on indicators, focusing on candlestick patterns, momentum candles, and price behavior at support/resistance and supply/demand zones. It assesses level strength through sharp reactions, fakeouts, and sequences like higher lows before breakouts, revealing real-time market sentiment and control.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Observe real-time candle behavior as price approaches or tests key levels (support, resistance, supply/demand zones, break points).",
    "Evaluate momentum via real body size: longer bodies indicate stronger buying/selling pressure; a momentum candle has a real body at least twice the size of the previous candles.",
    "At support: a long lower wick with small body near the high, or a hammer, signals rejection of lower prices; a bullish candle closing above a support level after wicking below confirms buying pressure.",
    "At resistance: a long upper wick with small body near the low, or a shooting star, signals rejection of higher prices; a bearish candle closing below resistance after wicking above confirms selling pressure.",
    "A doji (very small real body, long wicks) signals indecision.",
    "Decreasing real body sizes over consecutive candles indicate weakening momentum.",
    "A sharp move toward and away from a level (strong momentum candles into and out) suggests strength; a slow, gradual approach suggests weakness and potential break.",
    "Examine how price reacted the last time it touched a supply/demand zone: look for strong rejection, weak reaction, or a fakeout (brief break beyond zone followed by sharp reversal). Use the candle where the fakeout occurred as the zone’s starting point, and prioritize the most recent significant rejection over older boundaries.",
    "Before an upside breakout from a range, look for a sequence of higher lows forming near resistance. Before a downside breakdown, look for lower highs near support.",
    "A bullish candle that initially pushes up but reverses to close bearish (e.g., shooting star) indicates potential downside reversal.",
    "Confirm a bounce from support by seeing price move upward, not just a brief stall."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Price action provides real-time confirmation or rejection of key levels, helping traders gauge whether support/resistance will hold or break. Sharp, aggressive candles validate entries (e.g., long at support), while hesitation warns to wait or consider reversals. It refines supply/demand zone placement by incorporating reaction strength, reduces false signals from indicators, and improves entry timing, stop-loss placement, and breakout trade probability by distinguishing genuine breakouts from false ones.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Relying solely on indicators (e.g., RSI, MACD) without waiting for price action confirmation at key levels, leading to false signals.",
    "Misjudging candle strength by ignoring wick length differences or assuming only large momentum candles indicate strong reactions.",
    "Treating a slow, gradual approach to a level as a sign of strength, when it suggests the level may break.",
    "Using a fixed rule (e.g., always three candles) for zone placement without considering actual price behavior, ignoring fakeouts and recent rejections.",
    "Treating doji candles as reliable reversal signals without additional confirmation of trend exhaustion.",
    "Confusing price action with market structure: focusing only on past traces instead of current candle strength and momentum.",
    "Failing to distinguish between aggressive and hesitant price action at the same level, leading to premature or misguided trades.",
    "Assuming candlestick movements are linear; ignoring that intra-candle price can be erratic.",
    "Misinterpreting a small pullback as a reversal without seeing actual bullish candlestick patterns (e.g., higher lows, close off the low)."
  ],
